Figure 1A depicts the schematic diagram of our basic planar PSC scheme. From top to bottom, the structure is stacked by a transparent indium tin oxide (ITO) electrode, a compact titanium dioxide (TiO2) layer, a methylammonium lead iodide perovskite (CH3NH3PBI3) film, an N,N-di(4-methoxyphenyl)amino]-9,9′-spirobifluorene (spiro-OMeTAD) layer, and a silver (Ag) rear electrode. The incident light enters the cell from the ITO layer and is absorbed by the perovskite film to some extent. Also, the incoming light experiences a multireflection because of the rear Ag reflector which gives rise to an absorption enhancement. To quantity the interaction between electromagnetic waves and the layers, as well as the electric field (E) distribution, the Helmholtz equation (represented as follows) was solved:∇×∇×E-k02εrE=0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
